mutant
======
Platform : KUBSTU CTF
Category : Forensics 
Difficulty: Medium
Flag     : KubSTU{pdf_0bj3ct_m4st3r_v2}

------------------------------------------------------------------
THE CHALLENGE
------------------------------------------------------------------

We were given a file called crypt.pdf. It looked like standard
educational material for an information security exam. The name
"Mutant" suggested something was hidden inside the file structure
using non-standard methods.

------------------------------------------------------------------
STEP 1 -- SURFACE CHECKS
------------------------------------------------------------------

Before diving into the PDF internals, we ran the standard
first-pass checks that catch easy wins.

    exiftool crypt.pdf
    strings crypt.pdf | grep -i "kubstu\|flag\|ctf"

Neither returned a flag. Author, Title, and other metadata fields
contained only legitimate-looking content. No plaintext flag
embedded in the string output.

    binwalk crypt.pdf

binwalk confirmed a standard PDF header at offset 0 and found
nothing appended to the tail. No ZIP, no PNG, no second file
hiding inside. This is not a polyglot file.

Remember: always run these three commands first on any forensics
challenge file. exiftool catches flags hidden in metadata fields.
strings catches flags stored as plaintext anywhere in the binary.
binwalk catches nested files appended after the real file ends.
If all three return nothing, the hiding method is more subtle and
you need to go deeper into the file format itself.

------------------------------------------------------------------
STEP 2 -- INSPECT THE RAW PDF STRUCTURE
------------------------------------------------------------------

PDFs are text-based at their core. You can read the raw content
directly. We opened the file in a text editor and searched for
anything unusual.

    cat crypt.pdf | less

PDF comments start with the % character. Standard PDFs have a
few comment lines at the top (%PDF-1.x, %%EOF). We found an
extra comment block containing a large encoded string that had
no business being there. It started with <~ and ended with ~>.

That is the signature of Ascii85 encoding, also called Base85
(Adobe variant). This is not something that appears in a normal
PDF comment. The data was hidden here because casual inspection
of the PDF in a viewer shows nothing -- viewers render the visual
content and completely ignore comment blocks.

Remember: the % character in a PDF marks everything after it on
that line as a comment, ignored by PDF renderers. This makes
comments invisible to anyone viewing the file normally. They are
only visible when you read the raw bytes. Always run cat or
strings and grep for large blocks of non-standard characters
in PDF challenges. The <~ and ~> delimiters are a reliable
Ascii85 signature.

------------------------------------------------------------------
STEP 3 -- DECODE THE ASCII85 BLOCK
------------------------------------------------------------------

We extracted the full encoded string from the comment block and
decoded it. Two options:

Option A -- CyberChef (no code needed):
    Paste the string into CyberChef
    Apply the recipe: From Base85 (Adobe variant)
    Download the output

Option B -- Python one-liner:

    python3 -c "
    import base64
    data = b'Gat\$\$gMS6...'   # full string from the PDF comment
    print(base64.b85decode(data).decode())
    "

The decoded output was a text file we saved as decoded_output.txt.

Remember: Python's base64.b85decode() handles the Adobe Ascii85
variant used by PDFs. The encoded string must not include the
<~ and ~> wrapper delimiters -- strip those before passing it to
the decoder. If you get a decoding error, check that you copied
the full string without any line breaks or spaces introduced by
the text editor.

------------------------------------------------------------------
STEP 4 -- ANALYZE THE DECODED PDF OBJECTS
------------------------------------------------------------------

The decoded text contained raw PDF text-positioning operators.
Each line placed a single character at specific coordinates on
a page using the PDF graphics model:

    BT 1 0 0 1 50 100 Tm (K) Tj ET
    BT 1 0 0 1 62 100 Tm (u) Tj ET
    BT 1 0 0 1 74 100 Tm (b) Tj ET
    ...

Breaking down the syntax:
    BT          = Begin Text block
    Tm          = Text Matrix (sets position: x y)
    (char) Tj   = draw character at current position
    ET          = End Text block

The coordinates are: x position, then y position (height).
Different y values place text at different vertical levels on
the page.

Remember: PDF uses a coordinate system where y=0 is the bottom
of the page and y increases upward. Text placed at y=100 appears
near the bottom. Text at y=450 appears near the top. When you
see many Tj operators at different y coordinates in decoded PDF
content, sort them by y value to separate distinct text layers
from each other.

------------------------------------------------------------------
STEP 5 -- FILTER OUT THE DECOYS
------------------------------------------------------------------

We grouped all characters by their y coordinate:

    grep "Tj" decoded_output.txt | sort -k6 -n

Three distinct layers appeared:

    y = 450  ->  CTF{you_are_close_but_not_yet}
    y = 300  ->  FAKE{this_is_not_the_flag_try_harder}
    y = 100  ->  KubSTU{pdf_0bj3ct_m4st3r_v2}

The first two are decoys placed at higher y values to catch
solvers who stop at the first flag-shaped string they find.
The real flag sits at y=100, the lowest layer.

We extracted only the y=100 characters in x-coordinate order:

    grep "100 Tm" decoded_output.txt | grep -oP '\(\w\)' | tr -d '()'

Output: K u b S T U { p d f _ 0 b j 3 c t _ m 4 s t 3 r _ v 2 }

Remember: CTF challenges that hide data inside decoded payloads
almost always include decoy strings to waste your time. When you
see multiple flag-shaped outputs from the same source, extract
ALL of them, identify the one matching the exact known flag
format (KubSTU{ for this CTF), and verify it sorts correctly
by whatever coordinate or ordering the data uses. Never submit
the first flag-looking string you find without checking the rest.

------------------------------------------------------------------
FULL COMMAND SEQUENCE
------------------------------------------------------------------

    exiftool crypt.pdf
    strings crypt.pdf | grep -i "kubstu\|flag\|ctf"
    binwalk crypt.pdf
    cat crypt.pdf | less
    -> find % comment block with <~ ... ~> encoded string
    -> copy full encoded string to data.txt, strip <~ and ~>

    python3 -c "
    import base64
    data = open('data.txt','rb').read().strip()
    print(base64.b85decode(data).decode())
    " > decoded_output.txt

    grep "Tj" decoded_output.txt | sort -k6 -n
    grep "100 Tm" decoded_output.txt | grep -oP '\(\w\)' | tr -d '()'

